## Thread.Abort Migration → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — it spawns a thread, waits with `Join(timeout)`, then calls `Thread.Abort()` if it exceeds the deadline. Three APIs must go:

| Removed API | Why |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) |

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource with built-in timeout — fires Cancel() automatically
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

If `work` itself should respond to cancellation (recommended), accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    CancellationToken token = cts.Token;

    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token. Without checks, the task keeps running in the background even after timeout. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside `work`. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, raw socket reads, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept tokens. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks from the timeout callback. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Let it propagate everywhere else. |
| **Fire-and-forget task after timeout** | The old `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread. With cooperative cancellation, if `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion silently. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |

---

### Behavioral Difference

**Before (.NET Framework):** `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injected a `ThreadAbortException` at any point in the thread — the work stopped immediately regardless of what it was doing.

**After (.NET 8):** Cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking native call that never checks the token, it will **continue running in the background** after your method throws `TimeoutException`. This is the fundamental tradeoff — you gain stability (no torn state from mid-instruction aborts) but lose the ability to force-stop uncooperative code within the same process.
